1
00:00:11,735 --> 00:00:13,556
Hi, so I'm Tony Howard Arias.

2
00:00:13,556 --> 00:00:19,639
I am the co-writer and game designer for Scarlet Hollow, which is a choice-driven horror visual

3
00:00:19,639 --> 00:00:26,243
novel that sits at the intersection of Twin Peaks, Gravity Falls, and Life is Strange.

4
00:00:26,523 --> 00:00:29,245
It's really weird to be in front of a crowd like this

5
00:00:29,245 --> 00:00:31,927
after the past couple years, so forgive me

6
00:00:31,927 --> 00:00:34,288
if I get a little nervous.

7
00:00:34,288 --> 00:00:39,392
And I'm here to talk about ways to think about player choice

8
00:00:39,392 --> 00:00:42,694
in your choice-driven narrative games in terms of both making

9
00:00:42,694 --> 00:00:44,696
it feel like the decisions in your game

10
00:00:44,696 --> 00:00:48,758
matter to your players and not burning yourself out

11
00:00:48,758 --> 00:00:52,701
or being unable to finish your project because of just,

12
00:00:52,701 --> 00:00:53,622
like, scope creep.

13
00:00:54,722 --> 00:00:59,764
So to do a bit of an overview, when you're working on a choice-driven game, it's always

14
00:00:59,764 --> 00:01:05,006
going to be a balancing act between maintaining your cohesive narrative, making sure your

15
00:01:05,006 --> 00:01:10,188
choices fall within the cohesive story you're trying to tell, the struggles of exponential

16
00:01:10,188 --> 00:01:16,030
scaling, so if you have too many major decisions, incredibly easy for that to just get out of

17
00:01:16,030 --> 00:01:20,872
hand and lead to an unfinishable project, and then, of course, delivering impact for

18
00:01:20,872 --> 00:01:21,532
your choices.

19
00:01:21,992 --> 00:01:24,193
And impact is the term I'd like to use here

20
00:01:24,193 --> 00:01:28,093
to describe the measure of your players feeling

21
00:01:28,093 --> 00:01:31,454
like the choices in your game matter.

22
00:01:31,454 --> 00:01:33,574
Something I want to stress to the above point

23
00:01:33,574 --> 00:01:36,395
is that as narrative designers for video games,

24
00:01:36,395 --> 00:01:38,135
we are not tabletop GMs.

25
00:01:38,135 --> 00:01:42,516
And by nature, our medium is limited by finite choice

26
00:01:42,516 --> 00:01:46,237
because we can't just go off and immediately react

27
00:01:46,237 --> 00:01:47,277
to what our players are doing.

28
00:01:47,277 --> 00:01:50,318
So you have to make sure that your choices count.

29
00:01:50,938 --> 00:01:54,199
Building on that, creating impact is a function of knowing

30
00:01:54,199 --> 00:01:58,000
when you need to put in the blood, sweat, and tears

31
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,242
it takes to really make your narrative branch out

32
00:02:01,242 --> 00:02:05,483
in interesting ways, and knowing when to use misdirection

33
00:02:05,483 --> 00:02:09,184
and illusion to make your players feel like there's

34
00:02:09,184 --> 00:02:12,766
a lot more while still managing the scope of your project.

35
00:02:13,386 --> 00:02:19,932
um something to speak to on that note is that you know your back end, you know how things work,

36
00:02:19,932 --> 00:02:26,278
your players don't, which is both a blessing and a curse. Cause in some ways they will assume

37
00:02:26,278 --> 00:02:32,483
things work differently and that it's easier to make more branching than you actually can, but

38
00:02:32,483 --> 00:02:37,648
you can also find interesting ways to surprise your players and keep them guessing.

39
00:02:38,829 --> 00:02:44,394
All of this, creating impact, comes down to player emotions.

40
00:02:44,394 --> 00:02:46,816
At the end of the day, it doesn't matter

41
00:02:46,816 --> 00:02:50,619
if you have a massive fork at the beginning of your story

42
00:02:50,619 --> 00:02:54,543
that leads to 100,000 words of different content

43
00:02:54,543 --> 00:02:57,525
in either direction, because if people don't feel

44
00:02:57,525 --> 00:03:00,388
like that's the case, you haven't succeeded at your job.

45
00:03:01,189 --> 00:03:07,074
So focusing in on those emotions, knowing your players, paying attention to their feedback,

46
00:03:07,074 --> 00:03:11,698
and understanding why they feel the way they do is vital here.

47
00:03:11,698 --> 00:03:17,363
Now we're going to talk about impact, kind of of three varieties or techniques.

48
00:03:17,583 --> 00:03:23,672
I like to refer to these as cascades, callbacks, and heuristics, and we'll be going in depth

49
00:03:23,672 --> 00:03:27,217
in each of them, and we will be defining each of them as we go.

50
00:03:27,217 --> 00:03:30,422
We're going to start with cascades, which...

51
00:03:31,931 --> 00:03:36,113
I would define as what most people are talking about

52
00:03:36,113 --> 00:03:39,134
when they reference a big decision in a game

53
00:03:39,134 --> 00:03:42,636
or say that choices matter in a game.

54
00:03:42,636 --> 00:03:46,018
Choices in a cascading decision generally promise

55
00:03:46,018 --> 00:03:48,679
to permanently alter the game or world

56
00:03:48,679 --> 00:03:51,080
that the game takes place in in a major way.

57
00:03:51,360 --> 00:03:57,226
So taking an example of the first big cascading decision in our game, you run into monsters

58
00:03:57,226 --> 00:04:05,434
in the woods and you are stuck with the dilemma of saving a farmer or saving an adorable 17-year-old

59
00:04:05,434 --> 00:04:10,319
pug who, depending on how you've built your character, maybe you can talk to the pug too.

60
00:04:10,319 --> 00:04:11,400
Most people save the pug.

61
00:04:14,195 --> 00:04:16,736
In terms of what this looks like in our game,

62
00:04:16,736 --> 00:04:19,697
we've got the top path where you save the pug early on.

63
00:04:19,697 --> 00:04:22,998
You can see death of Duke the farmer.

64
00:04:22,998 --> 00:04:27,859
This leads to a breakaway scene with the police.

65
00:04:27,859 --> 00:04:33,161
It also leads to an encounter with his son later on,

66
00:04:33,161 --> 00:04:35,721
where you have to sort of justify and come to terms

67
00:04:35,721 --> 00:04:37,002
with the decision you've made.

68
00:04:37,002 --> 00:04:39,042
And Stella, your companion who owns the pug.

69
00:04:39,442 --> 00:04:43,805
continues to carry her around with her the rest of the game.

70
00:04:43,805 --> 00:04:49,508
So we're also differentiating that branch via different art assets.

71
00:04:49,508 --> 00:04:54,552
And then on the bottom you see the bummer path that not a lot of people get to see.

72
00:04:54,552 --> 00:04:57,673
Pug gets grabbed by monsters.

73
00:04:57,673 --> 00:05:01,756
Awful heart-to-heart conversation in the woods about what it's like to lose a dog.

74
00:05:01,756 --> 00:05:05,858
But you don't have to justify getting someone's dad killed.

75
00:05:06,434 --> 00:05:07,014
Yay.

76
00:05:07,014 --> 00:05:10,596
So there's a bunch of advantages

77
00:05:10,596 --> 00:05:12,718
to using Cascades as a primary technique.

78
00:05:12,718 --> 00:05:14,879
The first is that they're pretty easy to set up.

79
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:20,762
They are a situation with a limited number of choices.

80
00:05:20,762 --> 00:05:22,043
You should probably put a lot of care

81
00:05:22,043 --> 00:05:25,525
into what those choices are, but the setup is simple.

82
00:05:25,865 --> 00:05:27,685
They're also attention-grabbing.

83
00:05:27,685 --> 00:05:30,106
They're memorable, and they're the sort of thing

84
00:05:30,106 --> 00:05:31,306
people talk about.

85
00:05:31,306 --> 00:05:33,667
People will talk about whether they saved the pug,

86
00:05:33,667 --> 00:05:35,548
and they will admonish the folks who

87
00:05:35,548 --> 00:05:39,389
did not save the pug online.

88
00:05:39,389 --> 00:05:41,650
And because they're limited in scope,

89
00:05:41,650 --> 00:05:44,951
you usually only need to keep track of a single flag.

90
00:05:44,951 --> 00:05:47,492
Players, when they see one of these decisions,

91
00:05:47,492 --> 00:05:51,513
also know what they're going to be presented with.

92
00:05:51,513 --> 00:05:54,094
And if you actually pull it off, because these things are

93
00:05:54,094 --> 00:05:55,394
really hard to pull off.

94
00:05:55,740 --> 00:05:58,141
It's super impressive and again, people will talk about it.

95
00:05:58,141 --> 00:06:01,303
And that leads us to the challenges.

96
00:06:01,303 --> 00:06:04,805
The first is a scaling issue.

97
00:06:04,805 --> 00:06:07,646
Impacts that deviate too far from each other

98
00:06:07,646 --> 00:06:10,288
present exponential scaling problems with your narrative,

99
00:06:10,288 --> 00:06:13,770
especially if you have multiple cascading decisions

100
00:06:13,770 --> 00:06:15,250
like back to back in one game.

101
00:06:16,571 --> 00:06:22,397
Players have also been burned by games that say choices matter, like many, many times before.

102
00:06:22,397 --> 00:06:27,383
It doesn't matter how well you handle it, because folks have been burned, some people will get mad at you.

103
00:06:27,383 --> 00:06:33,689
These decisions, because they're major turning points, are also very emotionally charged,

104
00:06:33,689 --> 00:06:38,534
and again, some people will get mad at you for that.

105
00:06:38,849 --> 00:06:41,631
There's also, getting back to the scaling challenges,

106
00:06:41,631 --> 00:06:43,512
there is a delicate line to walk

107
00:06:43,512 --> 00:06:46,493
between making your cascades feel important,

108
00:06:46,493 --> 00:06:50,516
giving them impact, and being able to finish your game.

109
00:06:50,516 --> 00:06:53,297
It's also easy to over-promise and under-deliver

110
00:06:53,297 --> 00:06:55,318
because, again, people are familiar with this

111
00:06:55,318 --> 00:06:57,319
and they're going to hold you to very high standards,

112
00:06:57,319 --> 00:07:01,902
and pulling it off is both extremely labor-intensive and...

113
00:07:02,602 --> 00:07:05,505
subject to high levels of scrutiny,

114
00:07:05,505 --> 00:07:09,408
because there are always going to be few cascading decisions,

115
00:07:09,408 --> 00:07:12,451
and people are going to know what they are.

116
00:07:12,451 --> 00:07:15,453
That being said, we've got some tips and tricks

117
00:07:15,453 --> 00:07:17,035
for pulling them off, too.

118
00:07:17,035 --> 00:07:19,477
The most important one is for any sort

119
00:07:19,477 --> 00:07:21,138
of major decision in your game, you

120
00:07:21,138 --> 00:07:24,241
want to think about how you can write it to be modular.

121
00:07:24,241 --> 00:07:26,362
And when I'm using the word modular here,

122
00:07:26,362 --> 00:07:29,265
I'm talking about making it so that.

123
00:07:30,045 --> 00:07:33,867
bubbles of new content that come from that decision

124
00:07:33,867 --> 00:07:35,728
can slot into the main narrative.

125
00:07:35,728 --> 00:07:39,590
So you're not, instead of making, say,

126
00:07:39,590 --> 00:07:42,872
a tree or roots that expand forever,

127
00:07:42,872 --> 00:07:44,532
you're expanding a bit with new content,

128
00:07:44,532 --> 00:07:46,493
you're contracting to a common point,

129
00:07:46,493 --> 00:07:47,634
and you're expanding again.

130
00:07:47,634 --> 00:07:50,075
While you're doing this, it's important to think about

131
00:07:50,075 --> 00:07:53,337
what purpose these decisions serve for your narrative.

132
00:07:53,857 --> 00:07:58,707
In a lot of ways, they can flavor your player's experience with your game.

133
00:07:58,707 --> 00:08:00,751
This slide indicates another.

134
00:08:01,172 --> 00:08:04,715
big cascading decision we have in episode three of our game.

135
00:08:04,715 --> 00:08:09,159
The premise of Scarlet Hollow is that you are coming to town

136
00:08:09,159 --> 00:08:10,960
for an aunt you've never met's funeral.

137
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:14,744
You've been invited by your cousin who's on the left there.

138
00:08:14,744 --> 00:08:16,345
She's a terrible person.

139
00:08:16,345 --> 00:08:19,508
She's really mean to you.

140
00:08:19,508 --> 00:08:21,670
And a major theme of the story is

141
00:08:21,670 --> 00:08:24,212
about what your relationship with her is.

142
00:08:24,212 --> 00:08:27,315
Do you try and build a bond?

143
00:08:27,315 --> 00:08:28,696
Do you brush her off?

144
00:08:29,322 --> 00:08:33,085
And in episode three, we have this central set piece

145
00:08:33,085 --> 00:08:35,607
that's a ghost hunt, and there's a decision of,

146
00:08:35,607 --> 00:08:38,489
do you invite her along with you?

147
00:08:38,489 --> 00:08:40,751
If you do, you get to experience this ghost hunt

148
00:08:40,751 --> 00:08:41,952
with her at your side.

149
00:08:41,952 --> 00:08:46,175
If not, you get this other spooky guy on the,

150
00:08:46,175 --> 00:08:50,418
I guess it's the right for you guys, to follow you as well.

151
00:08:51,186 --> 00:08:55,411
This kind of comes back to a later point on this slide,

152
00:08:55,411 --> 00:08:58,715
which is you should always avoid making people feel

153
00:08:58,715 --> 00:09:01,599
like they're losing content when they make these decisions.

154
00:09:01,599 --> 00:09:03,722
One of the biggest impacts you can think

155
00:09:03,722 --> 00:09:06,605
of a cascading decision having is a character death.

156
00:09:08,120 --> 00:09:10,541
And if a character dies, you should make content

157
00:09:10,541 --> 00:09:14,002
about their death, so it doesn't feel like people

158
00:09:14,002 --> 00:09:16,163
are min-maxing their playthrough to get

159
00:09:16,163 --> 00:09:19,324
as much content as possible.

160
00:09:19,324 --> 00:09:21,785
Talking, going back to what I mentioned earlier

161
00:09:21,785 --> 00:09:25,526
with kind of bubbles and coming back to a common ground,

162
00:09:25,526 --> 00:09:28,247
if you're making a choices matter game

163
00:09:28,247 --> 00:09:31,348
that you intend to finish, your story is always going

164
00:09:31,348 --> 00:09:33,649
to have to revert to the mean in some way.

165
00:09:33,649 --> 00:09:36,090
It's always going to have to join back together.

166
00:09:37,650 --> 00:09:40,711
but you can focus on making the process,

167
00:09:40,711 --> 00:09:44,732
the journey of that mean reversion more impactful.

168
00:09:44,732 --> 00:09:47,493
So again, with the episode three choice here,

169
00:09:47,493 --> 00:09:50,293
you get two very different perspectives

170
00:09:50,293 --> 00:09:53,834
on an hour long segment of the game

171
00:09:53,834 --> 00:09:56,095
that change the themes of the story

172
00:09:56,095 --> 00:09:58,075
and shine different lights

173
00:09:58,075 --> 00:09:59,856
on different parts of our mystery.

174
00:10:01,737 --> 00:10:05,001
The next type of impact I'd like to talk about are callbacks.

175
00:10:05,001 --> 00:10:06,983
These are really straightforward.

176
00:10:06,983 --> 00:10:09,286
A callback is a reference to something

177
00:10:09,286 --> 00:10:11,549
that happened earlier in a story,

178
00:10:11,549 --> 00:10:14,091
specifically to a player choice.

179
00:10:14,091 --> 00:10:16,174
But it makes this reference without interrupting

180
00:10:16,174 --> 00:10:19,077
the flow of the narrative or creating new scenes.

181
00:10:19,077 --> 00:10:21,220
The choice it can reference can be big.

182
00:10:21,981 --> 00:10:23,382
I like a cascade.

183
00:10:23,382 --> 00:10:25,785
Stella mentions, oh, you saved my pug.

184
00:10:25,785 --> 00:10:28,328
That's great, or is sad about it.

185
00:10:28,328 --> 00:10:29,690
Or it could be small.

186
00:10:29,690 --> 00:10:32,954
So the small example we have here is in episode one,

187
00:10:32,954 --> 00:10:37,159
when your cousin tells you that she is a coal magnate,

188
00:10:37,159 --> 00:10:40,523
you can respond by saying, hashtag girl boss.

189
00:10:41,244 --> 00:10:44,886
And then in episode three, she references the fact

190
00:10:44,886 --> 00:10:46,807
that you said hashtag girl boss, if that's

191
00:10:46,807 --> 00:10:48,288
something that you said.

192
00:10:48,288 --> 00:10:50,790
You can track all of these things with Boolean flags.

193
00:10:50,790 --> 00:10:51,831
That's pretty much it.

194
00:10:51,831 --> 00:10:54,093
There's a lot of advantages to using callbacks.

195
00:10:54,093 --> 00:10:56,614
The first is that they are one and done.

196
00:10:56,614 --> 00:11:00,157
So adding more of them is just linear scaling over time.

197
00:11:00,157 --> 00:11:02,959
You don't have to worry about five callbacks taking

198
00:11:02,959 --> 00:11:05,601
20 times the energy of one.

199
00:11:05,601 --> 00:11:07,082
You just do them.

200
00:11:07,082 --> 00:11:09,203
It changes a line or two of dialogue, and you're done.

201
00:11:10,344 --> 00:11:18,348
Because when, because writers, game writers often think about creating impact in terms of those cascading decisions earlier,

202
00:11:18,348 --> 00:11:24,431
these aren't as common, so your players also don't expect them, which makes it easy to under-promise and over-deliver.

203
00:11:25,812 --> 00:11:27,573
So with the episode three moment,

204
00:11:27,573 --> 00:11:30,555
a player sees that we tracked the fact that they said

205
00:11:30,555 --> 00:11:32,957
hashtag girl boss in episode one.

206
00:11:32,957 --> 00:11:35,399
Suddenly, they're taken aback, it's unexpected.

207
00:11:35,399 --> 00:11:38,341
They start wondering, what else are we tracking?

208
00:11:38,341 --> 00:11:41,984
So even though that's a small callback,

209
00:11:41,984 --> 00:11:45,586
it makes the breadth and depth of the experience

210
00:11:45,586 --> 00:11:46,907
seem a lot more significant.

211
00:11:46,907 --> 00:11:48,629
They're also personalized,

212
00:11:48,629 --> 00:11:50,130
and they make your players feel good.

213
00:11:51,070 --> 00:11:52,952
There's challenges with them too.

214
00:11:52,952 --> 00:11:56,837
You can't rely singularly on callbacks

215
00:11:56,837 --> 00:11:58,278
because then you have a script

216
00:11:58,278 --> 00:12:00,761
that is mostly just a straight shot

217
00:12:00,761 --> 00:12:02,422
and doesn't really deviate.

218
00:12:02,422 --> 00:12:04,885
People won't feel like their choices matter.

219
00:12:04,885 --> 00:12:08,289
You also need a lot of them for your players to notice.

220
00:12:08,289 --> 00:12:10,251
In Scarlet Hollow, we probably have.

221
00:12:10,779 --> 00:12:13,641
somewhere between 500 and 1,000 of these things

222
00:12:13,641 --> 00:12:15,822
scattered all throughout in the first couple episodes.

223
00:12:15,822 --> 00:12:21,006
And by extension, because you need a lot of callbacks

224
00:12:21,006 --> 00:12:23,947
to make them effective, they require a lot of flags

225
00:12:23,947 --> 00:12:27,850
and booleans in your code to cover all of your bases.

226
00:12:27,850 --> 00:12:29,971
Again, we use like 1,000 and track everything

227
00:12:29,971 --> 00:12:31,332
players can say.

228
00:12:31,332 --> 00:12:33,253
Writing-wise, they can also require

229
00:12:33,253 --> 00:12:35,235
you to have a bit of encyclopedic knowledge

230
00:12:35,235 --> 00:12:36,255
of your own narrative.

231
00:12:36,763 --> 00:12:42,367
and it can really break your brain if you rely on them too much, just keeping everything

232
00:12:42,367 --> 00:12:43,328
straight.

233
00:12:43,328 --> 00:12:45,650
That being said, there's a few tips and tricks for using these things.

234
00:12:45,650 --> 00:12:51,373
Something that we really like to do is specifically using callbacks to make our dialogue feel

235
00:12:51,373 --> 00:12:55,776
less awkward and to make conversations with characters flow better.

236
00:12:55,776 --> 00:13:00,540
If you say something that you'd already said earlier in the game to a character and they

237
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:02,181
call you out on that or they act...

238
00:13:02,521 --> 00:13:03,381
a little confused.

239
00:13:03,381 --> 00:13:05,342
That's something that doesn't actually take a lot of effort

240
00:13:05,342 --> 00:13:08,624
to put into your game, but it makes your characters feel

241
00:13:08,624 --> 00:13:09,164
more organic.

242
00:13:09,164 --> 00:13:12,426
And again, it makes the depth and breadth

243
00:13:12,426 --> 00:13:16,568
of what you're doing seem that much more impressive.

244
00:13:16,568 --> 00:13:18,609
I also just make it a general best practice

245
00:13:18,609 --> 00:13:23,411
to flag literally every single line of dialogue

246
00:13:23,411 --> 00:13:26,913
you can say in Scarlet Hollow with a unique Boolean,

247
00:13:26,913 --> 00:13:28,534
because you never know when something

248
00:13:28,534 --> 00:13:29,855
might come in handy later.

249
00:13:31,065 --> 00:13:34,489
Um, so, you know, pretty standard code stuff there.

250
00:13:34,489 --> 00:13:40,076
Make sure you name your variables in an easy to search and easy to break down way.

251
00:13:40,076 --> 00:13:46,163
Make sure that you're, you know, defining them and storing them in the right places.

252
00:13:46,163 --> 00:13:47,405
Um, all that good stuff.

253
00:13:48,267 --> 00:13:51,631
The third type of impact I'd like to talk about are heuristics.

254
00:13:51,631 --> 00:13:56,115
So if you've taken an introductory psychology course,

255
00:13:56,115 --> 00:13:58,258
this term might ring a bell to you.

256
00:13:58,258 --> 00:14:01,321
A heuristic is essentially a problem-solving technique

257
00:14:01,321 --> 00:14:05,125
that relies on simplification to quickly arrive at.

258
00:14:05,805 --> 00:14:09,526
something you might think is a good enough answer

259
00:14:09,526 --> 00:14:14,107
to a problem or question, often at the expense of accuracy.

260
00:14:14,107 --> 00:14:16,307
So to use a pretty standard example,

261
00:14:16,307 --> 00:14:19,328
you might think, I've only known one person,

262
00:14:19,328 --> 00:14:22,028
or I haven't known anybody who's been struck by lightning.

263
00:14:22,028 --> 00:14:24,929
I don't need to know the exact rate at which Americans

264
00:14:24,929 --> 00:14:26,889
are struck or killed by lightning every year

265
00:14:26,889 --> 00:14:30,330
to be able to say, it's really uncommon.

266
00:14:30,330 --> 00:14:31,450
It probably won't happen to me.

267
00:14:31,990 --> 00:14:35,192
An example of a heuristic that isn't working well is,

268
00:14:35,192 --> 00:14:36,753
I saw two news stories about people

269
00:14:36,753 --> 00:14:37,814
who were struck by lightning.

270
00:14:37,814 --> 00:14:40,495
It must happen all the time.

271
00:14:40,495 --> 00:14:44,498
The most common example you'll see of these things in games,

272
00:14:44,498 --> 00:14:49,100
especially visual novels, are affection meters.

273
00:14:49,100 --> 00:14:53,383
But doing that across one axis,

274
00:14:56,122 --> 00:14:57,482
has some issues.

275
00:14:57,482 --> 00:14:59,743
My biggest issue is it can't handle bootlickers.

276
00:14:59,743 --> 00:15:02,884
I think we've all played games where you're in a dating sim

277
00:15:02,884 --> 00:15:05,545
and instead of treating the character you want to romance

278
00:15:05,545 --> 00:15:11,027
as a human being, you spend some time thinking about

279
00:15:11,027 --> 00:15:13,527
what can I say to make this person like me,

280
00:15:13,527 --> 00:15:15,728
regardless of whether or not you're actually

281
00:15:15,728 --> 00:15:18,989
being authentic or you have those shared interests,

282
00:15:18,989 --> 00:15:20,230
which is something that I don't like.

283
00:15:20,953 --> 00:15:25,156
So our approach to this in Scarlet Hollow is we use a five-axis

284
00:15:25,156 --> 00:15:29,319
and ten-variable heuristic-based relationship system

285
00:15:29,319 --> 00:15:32,341
to measure the player relationship

286
00:15:32,341 --> 00:15:35,003
with every major character in the game.

287
00:15:35,003 --> 00:15:38,126
So to just talk about some of these axes,

288
00:15:38,126 --> 00:15:40,227
we have one that's like openness versus closeness,

289
00:15:40,227 --> 00:15:42,949
which is representative of the emotional trust

290
00:15:42,949 --> 00:15:45,251
and vulnerability of a relationship.

291
00:15:45,251 --> 00:15:47,312
And then we also have one that's, you know,

292
00:15:47,933 --> 00:15:52,776
agreeableness versus adversarialness, which is politeness versus headbutting.

293
00:15:52,776 --> 00:15:57,279
We have, um, you know, boldness versus passiveness.

294
00:15:57,279 --> 00:16:00,841
How brave does someone else think you are?

295
00:16:00,841 --> 00:16:05,504
Um, and then major decisions, uh, major decisions like ones that lead to

296
00:16:05,504 --> 00:16:08,866
cascading impact can change these variables in big ways.

297
00:16:08,866 --> 00:16:13,208
Going back to the episode one decision with a dog we were talking about, if

298
00:16:13,729 --> 00:16:16,690
you let Stella's dog get grabbed by monsters,

299
00:16:16,690 --> 00:16:20,473
she closes up emotionally.

300
00:16:20,473 --> 00:16:22,634
So it will be more difficult to get her

301
00:16:22,634 --> 00:16:24,696
to open up about her feelings,

302
00:16:24,696 --> 00:16:26,857
but she won't necessarily be hostile to you

303
00:16:26,857 --> 00:16:28,598
because that's measured across a different axis.

304
00:16:28,598 --> 00:16:30,760
And then on top of those major decisions,

305
00:16:30,760 --> 00:16:34,282
we also change these variables in smaller ways

306
00:16:34,282 --> 00:16:36,123
for pretty much every dialogue option.

307
00:16:36,984 --> 00:16:39,647
So you have two things working together,

308
00:16:39,647 --> 00:16:42,671
big relationship-defining events that move meters a lot,

309
00:16:42,671 --> 00:16:45,955
but then there are smaller ways to influence things.

310
00:16:45,955 --> 00:16:49,079
You don't need 10 variables to do this,

311
00:16:49,079 --> 00:16:51,281
and there's definitely some that I use

312
00:16:51,281 --> 00:16:52,783
more than others in our game.

313
00:16:52,783 --> 00:16:54,485
You probably want more than one or two.

314
00:16:55,600 --> 00:16:59,441
Some of the advantages to using a heuristic-based system

315
00:16:59,441 --> 00:17:00,382
in your game.

316
00:17:00,382 --> 00:17:05,363
First one is that people use them all the time in real life.

317
00:17:05,363 --> 00:17:08,144
If you think about your best friend

318
00:17:08,144 --> 00:17:10,745
and how you feel about them, you probably

319
00:17:10,745 --> 00:17:13,345
think about the general vibe they give you,

320
00:17:13,345 --> 00:17:15,866
instead of pulling up a list of every interaction

321
00:17:15,866 --> 00:17:18,747
you've ever had with them and remembering specific events,

322
00:17:18,747 --> 00:17:20,347
because that would be too much.

323
00:17:20,347 --> 00:17:22,228
So people are wired to think.

324
00:17:22,608 --> 00:17:29,472
using Heuristics, and if you use a system like that in your game, it can make your characters feel more organic.

325
00:17:29,472 --> 00:17:34,895
You also don't need to memorize or remember a thousand specific details like you do with callbacks,

326
00:17:34,895 --> 00:17:41,538
because again, you're using a system to simplify some of this. We have an example of

327
00:17:41,538 --> 00:17:43,659
how we call our system here, where

328
00:17:43,659 --> 00:17:48,522
it's character Kanika. She's kind of the scully of the group.

329
00:17:48,897 --> 00:17:55,025
has a very different vibe depending on how brave she thinks you are, how emotionally

330
00:17:55,025 --> 00:18:01,432
vulnerable she is with you, as kind of the events of the story chip away at her disbelief

331
00:18:01,432 --> 00:18:03,134
in the supernatural.

332
00:18:03,134 --> 00:18:08,481
So here we're actually able to call on multiple aspects of the relationship system to decide.

333
00:18:09,061 --> 00:18:11,823
Is that wall of skepticism breaking,

334
00:18:11,823 --> 00:18:13,324
or is she holding strong?

335
00:18:13,324 --> 00:18:17,347
You can also use these,

336
00:18:17,347 --> 00:18:19,669
you can use heuristics to add flavor and nuance

337
00:18:19,669 --> 00:18:22,291
to both cascades and callbacks.

338
00:18:22,291 --> 00:18:24,832
So with Stella and her dog,

339
00:18:24,832 --> 00:18:27,434
if you're talking about what happened in the woods,

340
00:18:27,434 --> 00:18:30,677
she might have different things to say,

341
00:18:30,677 --> 00:18:32,578
different things she trusts you with,

342
00:18:32,578 --> 00:18:34,579
depending on how you've built that relationship.

343
00:18:35,060 --> 00:18:37,940
So within that major kind of cascading impact,

344
00:18:37,940 --> 00:18:41,221
you have all of these little smaller deviations

345
00:18:41,221 --> 00:18:46,702
that again make the ocean of your game feel a lot vaster.

346
00:18:46,702 --> 00:18:50,063
Another really cool thing with them is they're

347
00:18:50,063 --> 00:18:51,764
essentially modular by nature.

348
00:18:51,764 --> 00:18:56,385
So you can slot them in wherever without deviating too much

349
00:18:56,385 --> 00:18:59,785
and you can construct them as sliding scales

350
00:18:59,785 --> 00:19:03,266
so you have a wide range of character reactions

351
00:19:03,266 --> 00:19:04,827
and relationships you can pull from.

352
00:19:05,427 --> 00:19:12,450
Using a few examples, what if somebody thinks you're super brave but really likes you in a romantic way,

353
00:19:12,450 --> 00:19:16,352
they might try and toughen up to impress you,

354
00:19:16,352 --> 00:19:21,354
versus if they don't think you're brave but they like you in a romantic way,

355
00:19:21,354 --> 00:19:25,536
they might be, you know, a little more open about their concerns.

356
00:19:26,560 --> 00:19:29,062
There's a bunch of challenges with these two.

357
00:19:29,062 --> 00:19:30,623
They're difficult to set up,

358
00:19:30,623 --> 00:19:33,404
so if you have hundreds of dialogue choices like we have,

359
00:19:33,404 --> 00:19:35,565
you need to think hundreds of times

360
00:19:35,565 --> 00:19:38,507
about how each of those choices impact another character

361
00:19:38,507 --> 00:19:39,468
and how they think about you.

362
00:19:40,094 --> 00:19:45,461
They also need cascades and callbacks to reach their full effectiveness.

363
00:19:45,461 --> 00:19:48,084
They're also only as good as your writers are.

364
00:19:48,084 --> 00:19:53,331
This is true of any kind of impact, especially in a game that's mostly writing, but it's

365
00:19:53,331 --> 00:19:58,417
much more pronounced here because your writers in any given scene might need to take...

366
00:19:58,938 --> 00:20:03,799
Keep three variations of how a character feels in mind,

367
00:20:03,799 --> 00:20:06,479
and think about how those variations might flow

368
00:20:06,479 --> 00:20:08,740
into each other or change the flow of a scene.

369
00:20:08,740 --> 00:20:10,640
This can create a lot of extra complexity

370
00:20:10,640 --> 00:20:12,000
in your narrative, which is a good thing,

371
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:14,341
but can make it harder to write.

372
00:20:14,341 --> 00:20:17,861
And if you over-rely on these and over-simplify

373
00:20:17,861 --> 00:20:22,722
the kind of human relationships you're tracking too much,

374
00:20:22,722 --> 00:20:25,483
it'll make your narrative feel too gamey.

375
00:20:25,483 --> 00:20:28,523
See my earlier bootlicker comments.

376
00:20:31,107 --> 00:20:35,032
So some tips and tricks to using heuristics.

377
00:20:35,032 --> 00:20:37,355
Once you have them set up,

378
00:20:37,355 --> 00:20:39,919
they're one of the more flexible tools in your arsenal.

379
00:20:39,919 --> 00:20:41,721
You can use them to do a lot of things.

380
00:20:41,721 --> 00:20:45,246
Some of the stuff we use are calling on them

381
00:20:45,246 --> 00:20:46,648
to contextually change.

382
00:20:47,069 --> 00:20:49,251
music in scenes.

383
00:20:49,251 --> 00:20:51,314
Going back to this last slide,

384
00:20:51,314 --> 00:20:54,177
this is spending some quality time with your cousin.

385
00:20:54,177 --> 00:20:57,762
The image on the left is you asking her a probing question

386
00:20:57,762 --> 00:20:58,803
when she hates you.

387
00:20:58,803 --> 00:21:01,947
And the image on the right is asking a probing question

388
00:21:01,947 --> 00:21:03,569
where she's starting to trust you.

389
00:21:03,569 --> 00:21:05,451
So in that scene, if you're entering...

390
00:21:05,852 --> 00:21:12,938
entering it with like a relationship that's warming up. We play you know a soulful guitar track that

391
00:21:12,938 --> 00:21:19,424
kind of reflects on the way her thoughts about you are changing otherwise it's her normal sort of

392
00:21:19,424 --> 00:21:22,126
plucky tense strings music.

393
00:21:23,002 --> 00:21:25,623
We also use them all the time to just change sprites.

394
00:21:25,623 --> 00:21:29,525
Like, we call on these things a bunch to change dialogue

395
00:21:29,525 --> 00:21:31,446
and to change what information people are giving you,

396
00:21:31,446 --> 00:21:34,248
but the same line of dialogue with a different sprite,

397
00:21:34,248 --> 00:21:36,609
especially if you're not using voice acting,

398
00:21:36,609 --> 00:21:40,111
completely changes the way your players

399
00:21:40,111 --> 00:21:42,072
will read that line of dialogue.

400
00:21:42,072 --> 00:21:45,554
So, pretty low effort there to change the flow of a scene

401
00:21:45,554 --> 00:21:48,375
and to make it feel more or less oppressive,

402
00:21:48,375 --> 00:21:50,697
warmer, colder, all of these other things.

403
00:21:52,910 --> 00:21:58,657
Mentioned this before, you can use them in conjunction with flag decisions to make them

404
00:21:58,657 --> 00:22:01,421
feel a lot more impactful.

405
00:22:01,421 --> 00:22:05,406
So if somebody lost a friend, how much are they willing to open up with you about it?

406
00:22:05,406 --> 00:22:11,033
How does your relationship with them change their perspective on the events that are happening

407
00:22:11,033 --> 00:22:11,313
to them?

408
00:22:12,875 --> 00:22:16,599
Another cool thing is you can use a heuristic-based system

409
00:22:16,599 --> 00:22:19,061
to change what options are available for big decisions

410
00:22:19,061 --> 00:22:20,843
that lead to cascades.

411
00:22:20,843 --> 00:22:22,524
So this image is from the end of episode three.

412
00:22:22,524 --> 00:22:24,546
You're confronted with a ghost

413
00:22:24,546 --> 00:22:27,269
that your great-grandmother killed,

414
00:22:27,269 --> 00:22:30,492
who wants years of your life to kind of be able

415
00:22:30,492 --> 00:22:33,995
to move on to the next world.

416
00:22:34,215 --> 00:22:41,118
Normally your options are to leave the ghost behind where it can be a dangerous haunting that can hurt people or to make this huge

417
00:22:41,118 --> 00:22:48,840
Sacrifice, but if your cousin is with you and you have built that relationship in the in that right way

418
00:22:48,840 --> 00:22:53,462
She'll stop you from stepping in and will take that burden upon herself. So that's

419
00:22:53,802 --> 00:22:59,464
That's a way to kind of take the accumulation of hundreds of decisions over the course of

420
00:22:59,464 --> 00:23:03,345
a five or six hour game and really make it add up to a new thing.

421
00:23:03,345 --> 00:23:04,425
More cool things.

422
00:23:04,425 --> 00:23:08,866
Yeah, saying it again, combine your heuristics with flags.

423
00:23:08,866 --> 00:23:12,967
You can also combine your heuristics with other heuristics.

424
00:23:12,967 --> 00:23:17,788
So we'll have a lot of checks that are based on, okay.

425
00:23:18,857 --> 00:23:22,078
One, what level of emotional openness

426
00:23:22,078 --> 00:23:25,159
does this character have with you?

427
00:23:25,159 --> 00:23:29,220
But then also, what are the other flavors there?

428
00:23:29,220 --> 00:23:31,920
With your cousin, a pretty common one is

429
00:23:31,920 --> 00:23:34,081
she'll start to warm up emotionally,

430
00:23:34,081 --> 00:23:35,101
but she'll still be combative

431
00:23:35,101 --> 00:23:37,522
because she's a combative person.

432
00:23:37,522 --> 00:23:40,562
So we'll look at both the information

433
00:23:40,562 --> 00:23:42,943
she's willing to share, but then the tone

434
00:23:42,943 --> 00:23:44,523
that she's willing to share it as well.

435
00:23:48,034 --> 00:23:50,396
And then another really neat thing you can do too

436
00:23:50,396 --> 00:23:52,759
is you can use your existing heuristics data

437
00:23:52,759 --> 00:23:54,600
to alter the way that, sorry,

438
00:23:54,600 --> 00:23:56,462
new decisions affect those numbers.

439
00:23:56,462 --> 00:23:58,624
So going back to that hangout with your cousin,

440
00:23:58,624 --> 00:24:02,047
your cousin doesn't respond well to people

441
00:24:02,047 --> 00:24:06,812
who are nice for the sake of being nice,

442
00:24:06,812 --> 00:24:07,452
and often

443
00:24:08,362 --> 00:24:12,227
kind of being overly nice harms the emotional bond

444
00:24:12,227 --> 00:24:13,909
you're forming with her,

445
00:24:13,909 --> 00:24:16,232
but once that bond's been strengthened,

446
00:24:16,232 --> 00:24:19,316
you being nice feels more genuine to her.

447
00:24:19,316 --> 00:24:23,001
So those other axes on the relationship chart

448
00:24:23,001 --> 00:24:24,943
will actually change.

449
00:24:25,223 --> 00:24:28,367
based on what other data is already in the system.

450
00:24:28,367 --> 00:24:30,689
So you can create rubber banding effects.

451
00:24:30,689 --> 00:24:32,971
And again, this is a way to simulate real life.

452
00:24:32,971 --> 00:24:36,634
The same thing said by someone you can't stand

453
00:24:36,634 --> 00:24:39,177
versus said by your best friend is going to feel

454
00:24:39,177 --> 00:24:42,280
very different and going to impact those relationships

455
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:46,424
in different ways.

456
00:24:46,424 --> 00:24:48,186
Just general takeaways from this.

457
00:24:49,807 --> 00:24:55,912
When we're making Scarlet Hollow, we make sure to use all three of those kind of perspectives

458
00:24:55,912 --> 00:25:03,879
on impact for how we shape our narrative, how we shape decisions, and how we shape relationships.

459
00:25:03,879 --> 00:25:05,701
It's so easy to focus on just doing one thing.

460
00:25:06,141 --> 00:25:10,104
But if you want players to really feel like the choices in your game matter,

461
00:25:10,104 --> 00:25:15,627
you have to come across, you have to come at it from like every single angle.

462
00:25:15,627 --> 00:25:19,029
It's not just enough to have a really effective cascade,

463
00:25:19,029 --> 00:25:23,792
they need to be caught off guard by, you know, a very meaningful callback.

464
00:25:23,792 --> 00:25:25,513
They need to be caught off guard by,

465
00:25:25,513 --> 00:25:29,116
I thought this playthrough was mostly the same in terms of major decisions,

466
00:25:29,116 --> 00:25:32,238
but actually it's different in terms of how characters are responding with me.

467
00:25:33,322 --> 00:25:35,743
When you're crafting these choices,

468
00:25:35,743 --> 00:25:39,744
it's important to remember that you're making a narrative game.

469
00:25:39,744 --> 00:25:41,805
You should be constantly asking yourself

470
00:25:41,805 --> 00:25:44,927
why your narrative benefits from interactivity,

471
00:25:44,927 --> 00:25:47,168
and you have to use the answers to those questions

472
00:25:47,168 --> 00:25:49,849
to guide your design process.

473
00:25:49,849 --> 00:25:52,530
It's easy to just throw 50 choices on a screen,

474
00:25:52,530 --> 00:25:54,811
but you have to think about what the choices you

475
00:25:54,811 --> 00:25:55,932
present your players.

476
00:25:56,712 --> 00:25:59,854
will tell you, tell them, and tell your game

477
00:25:59,854 --> 00:26:03,517
about how they're engaging with your story.

478
00:26:03,517 --> 00:26:05,858
And the most important question of all

479
00:26:05,858 --> 00:26:09,320
is that throughout all of this, you should always

480
00:26:09,320 --> 00:26:10,221
be thinking about scale.

481
00:26:10,221 --> 00:26:12,882
What's the most important way that you can add just

482
00:26:12,882 --> 00:26:15,084
a little more impact to a choice or scene

483
00:26:15,084 --> 00:26:16,665
without breaking your back?

484
00:26:16,665 --> 00:26:19,226
Again, it is a balancing act.

485
00:26:20,064 --> 00:26:27,083
and it is very easy to get yourself stuck in a hole where you're never going to finish your game.

486
00:26:28,658 --> 00:26:29,738
That's the high level.

