565
00:30:59,440 --> 00:31:05,346
that kind of, uh, pigeonholes the design process in a lot of ways. I think it puts you in a

566
00:31:05,346 --> 00:31:06,908
lot of scenarios where

567
00:31:07,408 --> 00:31:12,650
You should have more, uh, options to respond in dialogue than you do, and then a lot of

568
00:31:12,650 --> 00:31:18,191
other scenarios where you have too many. Uh, so I try and go on a case-by-case basis and

569
00:31:18,191 --> 00:31:22,892
just think about what are the range, if I say we're DMing this game instead of coding

570
00:31:22,892 --> 00:31:26,673
it, what's the range of player responses I could expect?

571
00:31:27,274 --> 00:31:34,282
And then I also watch too many people stream our games, so I use that to sort of broaden

572
00:31:34,282 --> 00:31:42,091
the perspective of what kind of choices people are consistently making.

573
00:31:42,091 --> 00:31:45,035
Yeah, and then I also like, I personally...

